'''''SimRefinery''''' is a computer [[construction and management simulation games|management simulation game]] designed to simulate [[Chevron Corporation]]'s refinery operation. It was developed by [[Maxis]] in 1993.<ref>[http://www.1up.com/do/feature?cId=3138907 null from 1UP.com<!-- Bot generated title -->] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20070927192718/http://www.1up.com/do/feature?cId=3138907 |date=2007-09-27 }}</ref>

''SimRefinery'' was developed by Maxis after the success of ''[[SimCity (1989 video game)|SimCity]]''. After rejecting several requests from companies, the team eventually agreed to make a prototype for Chevron. In the words of [[Will Wright (game designer)|Will Wright]]:

{{quote|[''SimRefinery'' was] a simulation of their refinery operation, for orienting people in the company as to how a refinery works. It wasn't so much for the engineers as it was for the accountants and managers who walked through this refinery every day and didn't know what these pipes were carrying.|<ref>[https://www.wired.com/wired/archive/2.01/wright.html Interview with Will Wright] retrieved from [[Wired.com]]</ref>}}

The user's role in the simulation was the plant manager of a refinery.  One of the things the user learned was about [[supply and demand]] and how it affects the financial situation.<ref>[http://www.secinfo.com/dsVsd.8Ex.htm SEC Info - Gvi Security Solutions Inc - 10-K - For 12/31/96<!-- Bot generated title -->]</ref>

As a commissioned business aid, it was not made available to the public.<ref>[http://www.thefreelibrary.com/The+coming+green+computers-a014896038 The coming green computers. - Free Online Library<!-- Bot generated title -->]</ref>

''SimRefinery'' resembled ''SimCity'' with different graphics, disasters and rules; the latter to represent oil tanker ports, petroleum storage and piping systems.<ref>[http://art.net/~hopkins/Don/simcity/WillWright.html Transcription] of Will Wright's talk at [[Stanford University]]</ref>

